"Meyer D.E., Curran M.A., Gonzalez M.A.","An examination of existing data for the industrial manufacture and use of nanocomponents and their role in the life cycle impact of nanoproducts",2009,"Environmental Science and Technology","43","5",,"1256","1263",,,10.1021/es8023258,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-64349115294&partnerID=40&md5=f8f0a7088a09508506253a0d101620d8","U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, National Risk Management Research Laboratory, 26 W. Martin Luther King Drive, Cincinnati, OH 45268, United States","Meyer, D.E., U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, National Risk Management Research Laboratory, 26 W. Martin Luther King Drive, Cincinnati, OH 45268, United States; Curran, M.A., U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, National Risk Management Research Laboratory, 26 W. Martin Luther King Drive, Cincinnati, OH 45268, United States; Gonzalez, M.A., U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, National Risk Management Research Laboratory, 26 W. Martin Luther King Drive, Cincinnati, OH 45268, United States","This work examines the manufacture and use of nanocomponents and how they can affect the life cycle impact of resulting nanoproducts. Available data on the production of nanoproducts and nanocomponents are used to identify the major groups of nanocomponents studied in this paper: inorganic nanoparticles, carbon-based nanomaterials, and specialty/composite materials. A comparison of existing results for life cycle assessments of nanocomponents and nanoproducts is used to possibly identify trends in nanomanufacturing based on material grouping with regard to nonrenewable energy use and greenhouse gas emissions. Continuing work is needed in this area to incorporate other factors such as toxicity and resource consumption in addition to energy use and global warming potential to fully understand the role of nanomanufacturing in the life cycle of nanoproducts. © 2009 American Chemical Society.",,"Carbon-based; Energy use; Global warming potentials; Green house gas emissions; Inorganic nanoparticles; Life cycle impacts; Life-cycle assessments; Nano-manufacturing; Nano-materials; Nanoproducts; Non-renewable energies; Resource consumption; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Leakage (fluid); Nanoparticles; Nanostructured materials; Life cycle; nanoparticle; energy use; greenhouse gas; life cycle analysis; resource use; environment; greenhouse gas; life cycle; nanofabrication; review; synthesis; Carbon; Greenhouse Effect; Industry; Inorganic Chemicals; Nanoparticles; Nanostructures; Nanotechnology; Nanotubes",,"Carbon, 7440-44-0; Inorganic Chemicals",,,,"Schmid, K., Riediker, M., Use of Nanoparticles in Swiss Industry: A Targeted Survey (2008) Environ. Sci. Technol, 42 (7), pp. 2253-2260; Nanowerk Nanomaterial Database Search, , http://www.nanowerk.com/phpscripts/n-dbsearch.php, Available at; http://www.nanotechproject.org/inventories/consumer, The Project on Emerging Nanotechnologies Consumer Products Inventory. Available atNowack, B., Bucheli, T.D., Occurrence, behavior and effects of nanoparticles in the environment (2007) Environ. Pollut, 150 (1), pp. 5-22; Wiesner, M.R., Lowry, G.V., Alvarez, P., Dionysiou, D., Pratim Biswas, P., Assessing the Risks of Manufactured Nanomaterials (2006) Environ. Sci. Technol, 40 (14), pp. 4336-4345; Turk, V., Kaiser, C., Schaller, S., Invisible but tangible? Societal opportunities and risks of nanotechnologies (2008) J. Cleaner Prod, 16 (8-9), pp. 1006-1009; Balbus, J.M., Florini, K., Denison, R.A., Walsh, S.A., Protecting workers and the environment: An environmental NGO's perspective on nanotechnology (2007) J. Nanopart. Res, 9 (1), pp. 11-22; Kreyling, W., Semmler-Behnke, M., Möller, W., Health implications of nanoparticles (2006) J. Nanopart. Res, 8 (5), pp. 543-562; Bauer, C., Buchgeister, J., Hischier, R., Poganietz, W.R., Schebek, L., Warsen, J., Towards a framework for life cycle thinking in the assessment of nanotechnology (2008) J. Cleaner Prod, 16